DHT Tracker

With many BitTorrent trackers moving from the original HTTP to the newer UDP protocol, it is harder to get torrents started via the Tor anonymity service which only supports TCP. Once your torrent client is in touch with at least a few peers, it can ask for other peers via the Peer Exchange protocol, but bootstrapping the first few peers is tricky.

There's an alternative to talking to a tracker to bootstrap communication called the Distributed Hash Table. Unfortunately, it also uses UDP and is therefore usually incompatible with Tor. However, this service provides a workaround, by receiving requests over the old HTTP protocol and doing lookups against the DHT on your behalf. To use it, add the following as a tracker to your client:

http://trackeryknvofs3m.onion/announce

This will return the results of a read-only lookup against the DHT. It may take a few minutes to get going; unlike a normal tracker, it doesn't have the result instantly available and has to talk to dozens to hundreds of peers to find the information you requested.
